To consolidate Hong Kong’s position as a leading Asian financial technology hub, the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) continues to actively implement various measures to promote the development and application of technology within the banking and payments industries. Key progress made this year includes:
- Promoting wider adoption of the Faster Payment System “Faster Payments System”;
- Facilitating the implementation of Open Application Programming Interfaces (Open APIs) in the banking sector;
- Connecting the Trade Finance Platform “e-Trade Connect” with the trade finance blockchain platform under the People’s Bank of China (PBOC), to promote the digitalization of trade finance;
- Researching the application of Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC) in cross-border payments;
- Exploring the technical feasibility of “Commercial Data Exchange” and researching new credit scoring models to help small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) access financing;
- Announcing a two-year plan to develop a larger and more diverse RegTech ecosystem, further promoting the application of RegTech;
- Strengthening talent cultivation; and
- Advancing cross-border FinTech collaboration.

The Hong Kong Monetary Authority's Exchange Fund Advisory Committee establishes the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) Preservation of capital;
(b) Ensuring that the entire monetary base is at all times fully supported by highly liquid dollar assets;
(c) Ensuring that sufficient liquidity is maintained to preserve monetary and financial stability; and
(d) Pursuing investment returns as much as possible, in accordance with the above (a) to (c), to safeguard the long-term purchasing power of the Fund.

During the audit process conducted in accordance with the Audit Office's auditing standards, I will apply professional judgment and maintain a professional skeptical attitude. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risk of material misstatements in the financial statements due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to support my opinion. Since fraud may involve collusion, falsification, intentional omission, false statements, or overriding of internal controls, the risk of not detecting material misstatements due to fraud is higher than the risk of not detecting those due to error;
- Understand the internal controls relevant to the audit in order to design appropriate audit procedures. However, this is not intended to express an opinion on the effectiveness of the group's internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Management Officer are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures made are reasonable;
- Determine whether the Financial Management Officer's use of the going concern basis for accounting is appropriate, and based on the audit evidence obtained, determine whether there are significant uncertainties related to events or circumstances that may cast significant doubt on the group's ability to continue as a going concern. If I believe that significant uncertainties exist, it is necessary to draw the users' attention to the relevant disclosures in the financial statements in the auditor's report. If the relevant disclosures are insufficient, I will issue an auditor's report with a non-unqualified opinion. My conclusion is based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of the auditor's report. However, future events or circumstances may result in the group being unable to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including the disclosures, and whether the financial statements fairly present the transactions and events;
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the group in order to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the group audit. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.

The preparation basis of these financial statements is based on the historical cost method, except for the following assets and liabilities measured at fair value:  
- Derivative financial instruments (Note 2.6);  
- Financial assets and financial liabilities recognized in profit or loss at fair value (Note 2.6);  
- Financial assets recognized in other comprehensive income at fair value (Note 2.6);  
- Gold (Note 2.10); and  
- Investment property (Note 2.11).
